prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: B6 continuum/line: BAL vs nonBAL quasars, Region 1
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: This is a project to measure the dust continuum in quasars with and without BAL troughs. We are testing the idea that BAL quasars are a phase in the life of a quasar rather than an orientation effect. If BAL quasar absorption arises at a certain evolutionary time of a quasar then BAL quasars should have a higher dust contribution when compared to the control sample that do not show BAL troughs.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
This is a project to measure the dust continuum in quasars with and without BAL troughs. We are testing the idea that BAL quasars are a phase in the life of a quasar rather than an orientation effect. If BAL absorption arises at a certain evolutionary time of a quasar then BALs should have a higher dust contribution when compared to the control sample that do not show BAL troughs.
Receiver(s): Band 6 (221 GHz)
Angular Resolution: ~0.5" at Band 6. The ACA is not needed for these observations since the sources are small.
Spectral Resolution: FDM mode with spectral averaging of 16 for a total bandwidth of 4x1875 MHz and a resolution of 7.813 MHz. This setup gives the same data rates as TDM though with a factor of 4 better resolution (~10 km/s versus 40 km/s).
Continuum (Band 6) Sensitivity: In Cycle 2, up to 150 sources may be observed in one science goal, provided the sources are less than 10" apart. In the sky observable by ALMA, we find the two regions with the highest number of BAL quasars within a 5? radius (10? diameter). Each region contains 22 BAL quasars. For our control sample we center on the two regions defined by the BAL samples and match non-BAL quasars within 4% of redshift and i-band magnitude. Each region contains 22 non-BAL quasars. The two regions contain 44 quasars each.
The dust continuum flux density can be estimated via Scoville 2012 (equation 8.26). This equation relates the mass of the ISM, redshift, frequency of observations and luminosity distance to the dust continuum flux density. The flux density is lowest at z~1 and increases at lower and higher redshift. Therefore, we make minimum flux density estimates using the minimum redshift of our sample, z=1.7. We calculate the mass of the ISM by scaling the black hole mass by the Mbulge-to-Mbh ratio and gas-to-stellar mass ratio. The bulge mass is chosen to be consistent with Mbh-Mbulge relation, where the minimum expected black hole mass is chosen to be 10^8 solar masses. We use the bulge mass as a proxy for the host galaxy stellar mass. High mass systems have lower gas to stellar mass ratios. Using a gas to stellar mass ratio of 3, we estimate the minimum ISM mass to be 2x10^11 solar masses. Therefore, these sources should have S230GHz > 2.1 mJy. We aim to get a S/N ~ 20, though because of our conservative estimates on the flux density we will likely get much higher S/N.
We set LO1 to the lowest possible value in Band 6 (221 GHz). Doing so maximizes the chance of the CO J=6-5 transition falling in one of the sidebands (~15% of our targets), since the average redshift of the sampleis 2.12. Our primary goal is to characterize the difference between the cool dust continuum of BAL and non-BAL quasars. However, to ensure maximum scientific output we request FDM mode with spectral averaging of 16 which gives the same data rates (also, aggregate bandwidth sensitivity and total time requested) as TDM though with a factor of 4 better resolution (~10 km/s versus 40 km/s).
Band 6 Observing Time: For Band 6, the ALMA sensitivity calculator, assuming thirty-four 12-m antennas and dual polarization, predicts 1.67 minutes integration per source to reach a 1 sigma = 0.1 mJy in the aggregate band. Each science goal of 44 sources would require about 1.22 hours of on-source integration, and 42.57 min of calibration and 30.93 minutes of overhead for a total of 2.45 hours per science goal (region). Our overheads are ~20% of the total time requested, which is within the limit (<30%) suggested in the ALMA Cycle 2 Proposer's Guide.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Broad absorption lines (BALs) seen in a significant subset of quasars represent the largest, most massive outflows observed. While these outflows likely play a significant role in both the evolution of the quasar and its host galaxy, little is known about their nature. Recent results over a range of wavelengths indicate that the simplest models --- unification by orientation and unification by time --- fail to explain all of the observations on their own. It has been difficult to fully explore their host star formation properties due to sensitivity limits restricting sample sizes and thus statistical power. ALMA changes this. We propose to definitively test whether the sub-mm properties, and thus star-formation rates, of BAL quasars are different from unabsorbed objects. This will greatly enhance our understanding of the role of geometry and evolutionary processes in the BAL subclass, thus allowing us to incorporate these objects into the feedback equation. Several other important secondary results will come from observations to meet our primary goal.
